## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement + `ThreadAbortException`/`ResetAbort` as control flow.

In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is a no-op. You must switch to **cooperative cancellation**.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### What changed and why

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(work, token)` | Tasks integrate with `CancellationToken`; threads don't |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.WaitAsync(cts.Token)` | Throws automatically when the token fires |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` (implicit via timeout) | `Thread.Abort` → `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cooperative cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed | No equivalent needed — cancellation is cooperative |

### ⚠️ Critical Pitfall

**Cooperative cancellation won't forcibly kill work that doesn't check the token.** If `work` is a long-running CPU-bound loop or a blocking I/O call, the task keeps running after the timeout — you just stop *waiting* for it.

To make `work` truly cancellable, accept and check a token:

```csharp
// Overload that passes the token to work
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;
    var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller cooperates:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Other pitfalls to watch

| Pitfall | Guidance |
|---|---|
| **Forgetting `using` on `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers. Always `using` or `Dispose()` in `finally`. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` in work** | Won't respond to cancellation. Replace with `Task.Delay(ms, token)` or `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)`. |
| **Blocking I/O (sockets, DB)** | Use async overloads that accept `CancellationToken`. Sync I/O is **not** interruptible. |
| **Unmodifiable code (3rd-party)** | Move work to a child `Process` and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout — the only way to forcibly stop uncooperative code. |
